Copilot Project Handoff: AWS ELBv2 Prod-to-DR Reconciliation Engine
We are building an enterprise AWS ELBv2 reconciliation engine that compares Production and DR across separate AWS accounts/regions and synchronizes the application delivery layer.
The end goal is one unified Python script, but we are currently debugging/refactoring one subsystem at a time.
Current architecture
Production and DR are separate AWS accounts and different regions.
The engine must compare:
Prod → DR

ALB / NLB
Target Groups
Listeners
Listener default actions
Listener rules
Rule priorities
Rule conditions
Certificates
LB attributes
TG attributes
Tags

It must not register backend targets. Target registration is intentionally skipped because DR compute targets are handled separately through DRS/manual recovery.
What already works
The previous script successfully handles:
Target group discovery
Target group matching
Target group sync
TG attributes
TG health check settings
TG tags
Certificate domain matching
Load balancer matching when DR LB already exists
Basic listener matching
Report generation
Dry-run/report-only modes
Rollback metadata framework

In one run, target groups showed:
26/26 target groups in sync


So the TG logic should be preserved, not rewritten from scratch.
Main blockers
Blocker 1 — Missing LB auto-creation
The script initially detected missing DR load balancers but did not create them. That was because the execution path logged manual review instead of calling a real create_load_balancer() function.
Later versions added LB creation, but subnet mapping blocked it.
The current blocker is subnet resolution.
The DR VPC has multiple private /23 subnets that look identical by generic metadata:

private = false/true match
CIDR mask = /23
available IPs ok
multiple candidates with same score

So the script fails safely because it cannot choose a DR subnet confidently.
Required subnet resolver behavior
Do not hardcode subnet IDs in config.
The resolver must use normalized subnet Name tags as the primary mapping signal.

eg:
Production:
Prod-App-Private-A
Prod-App-Private-B

DR:
DR-App-Private-A
DR-App-Private-B

Normalize both by removing environment tokens:

Prod-App-Private-A → app-private-a
DR-App-Private-A   → app-private-a

Resolution order should be:

1. Explicit mapping if provided
2. Normalized Name tag match
3. Role tag match if available
4. Public/private route behavior validation
5. CIDR mask validation
6. AZ/ordinal fallback
7. Scoring fallback
8. Manual review if still ambiguous



The config should allow mapping overrides, but not require them.
Blocker 2 — Listener rules not proving parity
The report currently shows:

listener_rules_total: 0

That is suspicious. It may mean:

Rules are not being discovered
Rules are being discovered but filtered out
Rules are not associated with matched listeners
Only default rules are being counted


This must be fixed before trusting “in sync.”
The engine needs a debug discovery mode that prints:

LB name
Listener protocol/port
Source rules discovered
Target rules discovered
Default rule yes/no
Non-default rule count
Rule priorities
Conditions
Actions

Real parity means:

LB → Listener → Default Action → Rules → Priorities → Conditions → Actions → TGs


Not just “LB object exists.”
