What Copilot should do next
First, fix config parsing so unknown or new fields do not crash the script.
Then implement these in order:


1. Discovery-only mode
2. Listener rule discovery debug output
3. Name-tag-first subnet resolver
4. Load balancer creation using resolved DR subnets
5. Listener creation/update
6. Listener rule create/update
7. Post-apply validation
8. Final unified single-file script


Do not run destructive operations.
Do not delete extra resources.
Do not register/deregister targets.
Do not modify Route 53.
Do not import certificates automatically.
Everything should be safe by default:


--report-only
--dry-run
--yes only when explicitly requested

Success criteria
The final engine succeeds when a dry-run can prove:


All source LBs matched or planned for creation
All source TGs matched/created
All listeners matched/created/updated
All listener rules discovered
All listener rule priorities compared
All listener rule conditions compared
All listener actions remapped to DR TG ARNs
All HTTPS/TLS certificates mapped to DR ACM certs
No ambiguous subnet mappings
No unmatched routing dependencies

The report must distinguish:

LB object parity
Listener parity
Rule parity
Certificate parity
TG parity

Do not report “Load Balancer in sync” as full routing parity unless its listeners and rules are also in sync.